'''Borja Iglesias Quintas''' ({{IPA|es|ˈboɾxajˈɣlesjas}}; born 17 January 1993) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|striker]] for [[La Liga]] club [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta de Vigo]] and the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]].

Developed at [[RC Celta de Vigo|Celta]], where he played mainly in [[Celta de Vigo B|the reserves]] initially, he achieved totals of over 250 [[La Liga]] appearances and 75 goals for that club, [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]] and [[Real Betis|Betis]]. He won the [[2021–22 Copa del Rey]] with the latter.

Iglesias made his full debut for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in 2022.

==Club career==
===Villarreal===
Born in [[Santiago de Compostela]], [[Province of A Coruña]], [[Galicia, Spain|Galicia]], Iglesias began playing football as a toddler in his local primary school, until he was recruited by [[SD Compostela]] at age 10.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elcorreogallego.es/galicia/2019/06/27/borja-iglesias-anos-vida-cambiado-109892860.html|title=Borja Iglesias: "En dos años mi vida ha cambiado radicalmente, pero soy el mismo"|trans-title=Borja Iglesias: "My life changed dramatically in two years, but I am the same"|newspaper=[[El Correo Gallego]]|first=Óscar|last=De la Fuente|language=es|date=27 June 2019|access-date=2 May 2025}}</ref> He eventually graduated from [[Villarreal CF]]'s youth setup after stints at [[CD Roda]] and [[Valencia CF]], starting his senior career in 2012 with the former's [[Villarreal CF C|C team]] in the [[Tercera División]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/2018/10/02/primera/1538497872_319233.html|title=La primera vez de Borja Iglesias con su 'ex' y ante un amigo|trans-title=Borja Iglesias' first time with an 'ex' and against a friend|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Iván|last=Molero|language=es|date=2 October 2018|access-date=5 November 2021}}</ref>

===Celta===
Iglesias joined [[RC Celta de Vigo]] on 9 July 2013, signing a two-year deal with an option for a further three and being assigned to [[Celta de Vigo B|the reserves]] in the [[Segunda División B]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celtavigo.net/es/cantera/6635-el-delantero-gallego-borja-iglesias-nuevo-refuerzo-para-el-celta-b|title=El delantero gallego Borja Iglesias, nuevo refuerzo para el Celta B|trans-title=Galician forward Borja Iglesias, new addition to Celta B|publisher=RC Celta Vigo|language=es|date=9 July 2013|access-date=4 January 2015|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104035525/http://www.celtavigo.net/es/cantera/6635-el-delantero-gallego-borja-iglesias-nuevo-refuerzo-para-el-celta-b|archive-date=4 January 2015}}</ref> On 3 January 2015 he made his first-team – and [[La Liga]] – debut, coming on as a 78th-minute [[Substitute (association football)|substitute]] for [[Santi Mina]] in a 1–0 away loss against [[Sevilla FC]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/eventos/marcador/futbol/2014_15/primera/jornada_17/sev_cel/|title=Demasiado premio para el Sevilla|trans-title=Too much prize for Sevilla|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|first=Tomás|last=Campos|language=es|date=3 January 2015|access-date=4 January 2015}}</ref>

On 11 December 2016, after scoring a brace in a 3–2 away defeat to [[Caudal Deportivo]], Iglesias became Celta B's all-time top scorer with 53 goals, surpassing [[Goran Marić (footballer)|Goran Marić]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://celtavigo.net/en/11-cantera/11858-borja-iglesias-becomes-reserve-team-top-scorer-of-all-times|title=Borja Iglesias becomes reserve team top scorer of all times|publisher=RC Celta Vigo|date=14 December 2016|access-date=14 January 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116193510/http://celtavigo.net/en/11-cantera/11858-borja-iglesias-becomes-reserve-team-top-scorer-of-all-times|archive-date=16 January 2017}}</ref> He topped the [[2016–17 Segunda División B|third-tier charts]] at 32, being essential as his team sealed a [[2017 Segunda División B play-offs|play-off berth]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/mas-futbol/segunda-b-grupo-i/2017/05/18/591d7d4322601dfb768b4591.html|title=Celta B: Pólvora y más pólvora para dinamitar la fase de ascenso|trans-title=Celta B: Gunpowder and more gunpowder for blowing up the promotion play-offs|newspaper=Marca|first=Samuel|last=Galicia|language=es|date=18 May 2017|access-date=20 May 2017}}</ref>

On 6 July 2017, Iglesias was loaned to [[Segunda División]] club [[Real Zaragoza]] for one year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realzaragoza.com/noticias/acuerdo-con-el-celta-para-la-cesi-n-del-delantero-borja-iglesias|title=Acuerdo con el Celta para la cesión del delantero Borja Iglesias|trans-title=Agreement with Celta for the loan of forward Borja Iglesias|publisher=Real Zaragoza|language=es|date=6 July 2017|access-date=10 July 2017}}</ref> He scored his first goal for his new team on 27 August, the equaliser through a [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] in a 1–1 home draw with [[Granada CF]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canalsur.es/1-1-el-granada-logra-un-punto-en-zaragoza-gracias-a-la-actuacion-de-javi-varas/1192569.html|title=1–1. El Granada logra un punto en Zaragoza gracias a la actuación de Javi Varas|trans-title=1–1. Granada get one point in Zaragoza thanks to Javi Varas' performance|publisher=[[Canal Sur]]|language=es|date=27 August 2017|access-date=3 April 2018}}</ref> Additionally, he netted braces against [[Córdoba CF]], [[Sevilla Atlético]], [[Real Valladolid]] and [[CA Osasuna]], to reach 15 goals by March<ref>{{cite news|url=http://diarioaragones.com/deportes/pisandoarea/108712-borja-iglesias-ya-suma-15-goles-en-liga.html|title=Borja Iglesias ya suma 15 goles en liga|trans-title=Borja Iglesias already sums up 15 goals in the league|newspaper=Diario Aragonés|language=es|date=18 March 2018|access-date=27 March 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180328041121/http://diarioaragones.com/deportes/pisandoarea/108712-borja-iglesias-ya-suma-15-goles-en-liga.html|archive-date=28 March 2018}}</ref> and finish [[2017–18 Segunda División|the season]] as the division's joint-third highest scorer on 22.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/2018/05/24/5b06920bca4741d6648b466b.html|title=Un Pichichi de otra época|trans-title=A Pichichi of another era|newspaper=Marca|first=Chus|last=Rodríguez|language=es|date=25 May 2018|access-date=29 October 2021}}</ref> Earlier on 24 September, he was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] just before half time in a 1–1 draw with [[Gimnàstic de Tarragona]] at [[La Romareda]] for what the [[Referee (association football)|referee]] considered an aggression towards [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] [[Stole Dimitrievski]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/2017/09/24/59c8160be5fdeada0c8b45eb.html|title=El Zaragoza resiste al acoso del Nástic... y al árbitro|trans-title=Zaragoza resist Nástic's harassment... and the referee|newspaper=Marca|first=Sonia|last=Gaudioso|language=es|date=24 September 2017|access-date=29 October 2021}}</ref>

===Espanyol===
On 9 July 2018, Iglesias signed a four-year contract with [[RCD Espanyol]] with a [[buyout clause]] of [[Euro|€]]28 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rcdespanyol.com/ca/actualitat/borja-iglesias-nou-davanter-de-lespanyol/_n:7468/|title=Borja Iglesias, nou davanter de l'Espanyol|trans-title=Borja Iglesias, new forward of Espanyol|publisher=RCD Espanyol|language=ca|date=9 July 2018|access-date=12 July 2018}}</ref> He made his official debut for the club on 18 August, starting in a 1–1 home draw against former club Celta.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/primera-division/2018/08/18/5b7862b6268e3e98068b45ee.html|title=Tablas para ir calentando|trans-title=Draw to start preparing|newspaper=Marca|first=Delfín|last=Melero|language=es|date=18 August 2018|access-date=20 August 2018}}</ref> In his next appearance, he helped the hosts defeat [[Valencia CF]] 2–0 after profiting from a [[Cristiano Piccini]] mistake midway through the second half.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cadenaser.com/ser/2018/08/26/deportes/1535308396_811273.html|title=Granero y Borja Iglesias borran al Valencia|trans-title=Granero and Borja Iglesias wipe Valencia out|publisher=[[Cadena SER]]|language=es|date=26 August 2018|access-date=4 September 2018}}</ref>

Iglesias scored three goals over two legs in an aggregate 7–1 win over [[Stjarnan men's football|Ungmennafélagið Stjarnan]] in the [[2019–20 UEFA Europa League|second qualifying round]] of the [[UEFA Europa League]] in late July and early August 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/espanyol/2019/08/01/5d43567ae2704e304e8b4628.html|title=El Espanyol liquida al Stjarnan en la Europa League por la vía rápida|trans-title=Espanyol finish off Stjarnan in the Europa League through the fast lane|newspaper=Marca|first=Cristina|last=Navarro|language=es|date=1 August 2019|access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref>

===Betis===
[[File:Borja_iglesias_presentación_002.jpg|thumb|upright|Iglesias being presented by [[Real Betis|Betis]] in August 2019]]
On 14 August 2019, Iglesias moved to [[Real Betis]] after agreeing to a five-year deal for a fee of €28 million, reuniting with his former Espanyol manager [[Rubi (footballer)|Rubi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cope.es/deportes/futbol/noticias/borja-iglesias-llega-betis-tras-pago-clausula-espanyol-20190814_479240|title=Borja Iglesias llega al Betis tras el pago de su cláusula al Espanyol|trans-title=Borja Iglesias arrives at Betis after Espanyol release clause was met|publisher=[[Cadena COPE]]|language=es|date=14 August 2019|access-date=14 August 2019}}</ref> He struggled with just three goals as the team [[2019–20 La Liga|finished 15th]] in his debut campaign,<ref name=MAM>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/betis/2021/09/06/6135fc1922601d35328b463c.html|title=Borja Iglesias: "Si algún día consideran que puedo aportar en la Selección, me encantaría"|trans-title=Borja Iglesias: "If one day they consider that I can contribute to the national team, I would love it"|newspaper=Marca|first=Miguel Ángel|last=Morán|language=es|date=6 September 2021|access-date=29 October 2021}}</ref> and received a red card on 20 February at the end of a goalless draw at [[CD Leganés]] for pushing an opposition coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/spanish-football/2020/02/16/5e4963a046163f3da48b45fa.html|title=Borja Iglesias sees red for shoving Leganes assistant into the dugout|newspaper=Marca|date=16 February 2020|access-date=29 October 2021}}</ref> In 2020–21, he contributed 13 goals – 11 in [[2020–21 La Liga|the league]] – to clinch a [[2021–22 UEFA Europa League|Europa League place]].<ref name=MAM/>

On 3 March 2022, in the second leg of the [[2021–22 Copa del Rey|semi-finals]] of the [[Copa del Rey]] against [[Rayo Vallecano]], Iglesias scored in stoppage time to ensure his team a 1–1 draw and a spot in [[2022 Copa del Rey Final|the final]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/report/_/gameId/631531|title=Real Betis reach Copa del Rey final on late Borja Iglesias goal|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=3 March 2022|access-date=8 March 2022}}</ref> In the [[2022 Copa del Rey final|decisive match]] on 23 April, he opened a 1–1 draw with Valencia as his team won on [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalties]];<ref name=Cup>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/61202911|title=Real Betis 1–1 Valencia|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=23 April 2022|access-date=24 April 2022}}</ref> he also topped the tournament's individual charts at five,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/apuestas-deportivas/panda-aduena-copa-13558492|title=El Panda se adueña de la Copa|trans-title=Panda takes hold of the Cup|newspaper=[[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]]|language=es|date=24 April 2022|access-date=25 April 2022}}</ref> and was the final's most valuable player.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://todaytimeslive.com/sports/23010.html|title=Borja Iglesias, MVP of the Cup final|publisher=Today Times Live|date=23 April 2022|access-date=18 January 2023}}</ref>

Iglesias opened the [[2022–23 La Liga|2022–23 season]] with six goals in six games,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/apuestas-deportivas/el-corner-de-pronosticos/transformacion-borja-iglesias-le-llevado-75706828|title=La transformación de Borja Iglesias que le ha llevado a la selección española|trans-title=Borja Iglesias' transformation that has taken him to the Spanish national team|newspaper=Sport|language=es|date=20 September 2022|access-date=21 September 2022}}</ref> earning himself the accolade of [[La Liga Player of the Month]] for August.<ref name=August>{{cite web|url=https://www.laliga.com/en-GB/news/borja-iglesias-named-laliga-santander-player-of-the-month-for-august|title=Borja Iglesias named LaLiga Santander Player of the Month for August|publisher=[[La Liga]]|date=8 September 2022|access-date=9 September 2022}}</ref> On 6 November, both he and teammate [[Nabil Fekir]] (as well as [[Gonzalo Montiel]] for the opposition) received straight red cards in an eventual 1–1 home draw with Sevilla in the [[Seville derby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20221106-sevilla-hold-betis-in-fiery-derby-atletico-drop-points-again|title=Sevilla hold Betis in fiery derby, Atletico drop points again|publisher=[[France 24]]|date=6 November 2022|access-date=7 November 2022}}</ref>

Iglesias scored only twice from 18 appearances in the first part of [[2023–24 La Liga|2023–24]], failing to find the net in the domestic league.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.estadiodeportivo.com/futbol/europa-league/lamentacion-borja-iglesias-20231130-435876.html|title=La lamentación de Borja Iglesias|trans-title=Borja Iglesias' lament|newspaper=[[Estadio Deportivo]]|first=Manuel|last=Pedrero|language=es|date=30 November 2023|access-date=28 January 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.record.pt/internacional/paises/alemanha/bayer-leverkusen/detalhe/oficial-betis-empresta-borja-iglesias-ao-bayer-leverkusen|title=Oficial: Betis empresta Borja Iglesias ao Bayer Leverkusen|trans-title=Official: Betis loan Borja Iglesias to Bayer Leverkusen|newspaper=[[Record (Portuguese newspaper)|Record]]|language=pt|date=28 January 2024|access-date=28 January 2024}}</ref> On 27 January 2024, he was sent on loan to [[Bundesliga]] club [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen]] until the end of [[2023–24 Bundesliga|the campaign]], with a reported option to buy for €8 million;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bayer04.de/en-us/news/bayer04/bayer-04-sign-centre-forward-borja-iglesias-on-loan-to-the-summer|title=Bayer 04 sign centre forward Borja Iglesias on loan to the summer|publisher=Bayer 04 Leverkusen|date=28 January 2024|access-date=28 January 2024}}</ref> he arrived to cover for the injured [[Victor Boniface]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/bayer-leverkusen-sign-borja-iglesias-on-initial-loan-real-betis-26033|title=Bayer Leverkusen sign Spain striker Borja Iglesias on loan from Real Betis|publisher=[[Bundesliga]]|date=27 January 2024|access-date=27 January 2024}}</ref> He totalled ten games during his spell, winning a domestic [[Double (association football)|double]] but failing to score in the process.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/fichajes/20240525/1002253100/borja-iglesias-serie-pretendiente-espana.html|title=Borja Iglesias tiene un serio pretendiente en España|trans-title=Borja Iglesias has a serious suitor in Spain|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=Jordi|last=Santamaría|language=es|date=25 May 2024|access-date=27 May 2024}}</ref><ref name=Double>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/bundesliga/20240525/1002253240/kaiserslautern-bayer-leverkusen-el-partido-futbol-hoy-en-directo-copa-alemana-dfb-pokal-ext-pau.html|title=Kaiserslautern 0–1 Bayer Leverkusen: resumen, resultado y goles {{!}} Final de la Copa Alemana|trans-title=Kaiserslautern 0–1 Bayer Leverkusen: summary, result and goals {{!}} German Cup final|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Alberto|last=De la Ossa|language=es|date=25 May 2024|access-date=26 May 2024}}</ref>

===Return to Celta===
On 19 July 2024, Iglesias returned to Celta on a [[2024–25 La Liga|season]]-long loan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://as.com/futbol/primera/borja-iglesias-cedido-al-celta-n/|title=Oficial: Borja Iglesias, cedido al Celta|trans-title=Official: Borja Iglesias, loaned to Celta|newspaper=Diario AS|first=Clemente|last=Garrido|language=es|date=19 July 2024|access-date=22 July 2024}}</ref> He scored a squad-best 11 goals while veteran [[Iago Aspas]] added ten, and they [[2025–26 UEFA Europa League|qualified for the Europa League]] after finishing seventh;<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.elperiodico.com/es/deportes/20250524/celta-gana-billete-europa-league-117789145|title=El Celta se alza con el billete para la Europa League y el Rayo se va a la Conference|trans-title=Celta get ticket for the Europa League and Rayo go to the Conference|newspaper=[[El Periódico (Barcelona)|El Periódico]]|language=es|date=24 May 2025|access-date=29 May 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.estadiodeportivo.com/futbol/celta/borja-iglesias-deja-claro-celta-betis-20250524-496432.html|title=Borja Iglesias se lo deja claro al Celta y al Betis|trans-title=Borja Iglesias makes it crystal clear for Celta and Betis|newspaper=[[Estadio Deportivo]]|first=Fernando|last=Mateos|language=es|date=24 May 2025|access-date=29 May 2025}}</ref> this included his first [[hat-trick]] in the top division on 19 April 2025, a fruitless one as it was in a 4–3 away loss against eventual champions [[FC Barcelona]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/futbol/celta/2025/04/20/primer-hat-trick-borja-iglesias-maxima-categoria.html|title=Primer hat trick de Borja Iglesias en la máxima categoría|trans-title=First Borja Iglesias hat trick in the top tier|newspaper=Marca|first=Rafa|last=Valero|language=es|date=20 April 2025|access-date=29 May 2025}}</ref>

Iglesias signed a permanent two-year contract with the club on 12 August 2025, with an option for an additional year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rccelta.es/en/equipo/actualidad/borja-iglesias-returns-home/|title=Now yes: Borja Iglesias returns home|publisher=RC Celta Vigo|date=12 August 2025|access-date=12 August 2025}}</ref>

==International career==
In September 2022, Iglesias and [[Nico Williams]] were called up for the first time to the [[Spain national football team|Spain national team]], ahead of [[UEFA Nations League]] games with [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.co.uk/football/fifa-world-cup/story/4750771/world-cup-stock-watch-ronaldomane-fall-pepi-and-toney-rise-ahead-of-qatar-2022|title=World Cup stock watch: Ronaldo, Mane fall; Pepi and Toney rise ahead of Qatar 2022|publisher=ESPN|date=21 September 2022|access-date=21 September 2022}}</ref> He made his debut against the former, in a 2–1 loss in [[Zaragoza]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.beinsports.com/en/football/news/switzerland-secure-nations-league-upset-over-/1956778|title=Switzerland secure Nations League upset over Spain|publisher=[[beIN Sports]]|date=24 September 2022|access-date=25 September 2022}}</ref> Despite his 20 goals making him the top scoring national player of the calendar year, he was overlooked for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] – the first Spaniard since [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]] to be in this position.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mundodeportivo.com/futbol/betis/20221214/1001906793/borja-iglesias-cree-2022-sido-ano-he-jugado-mi-mejor-nivel-betis.html|title=Borja Iglesias cree que 2022 ha sido el año en "que he jugado a mi mejor nivel"|trans-title=Borja Iglesias believes that 2022 has been the year in "which I played at my best level"|newspaper=Mundo Deportivo|first=Jordi|last=Santamaría|language=es|date=14 December 2022|access-date=15 December 2022}}</ref>

In August 2023, in response to the [[Royal Spanish Football Federation]] president [[Luis Rubiales]] non-consensually kissing Spanish midfielder [[Jennifer Hermoso]] during the [[2023 FIFA Women's World Cup|Women's World Cup]] medal ceremony, Iglesias announced he would boycott playing for Spain until Rubiales resigned.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://english.elpais.com/sports/2023-08-25/spain-striker-borja-iglesias-steps-down-from-national-team-after-rubiales-refusal-to-resign.html|title=Spain striker Borja Iglesias steps down from national team after Rubiales' refusal to resign|newspaper=[[El País]]|date=25 August 2023|access-date=25 August 2023}}</ref> He returned to the squads in October 2025,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.infobae.com/espana/2025/10/06/borja-iglesias-vence-a-los-odiadores-con-su-regreso-a-la-seleccion-el-panda-reencuentra-en-vigo-la-punteria-y-la-felicidad/|title=Borja Iglesias vence a los odiadores con su regreso a la Selección: ‘El Panda’ reencuentra en Vigo la puntería y la felicidad|trans-title=Borja Iglesias beats haters with his return to the national team: 'The Panda' rediscovers scoring touch and happiness in Vigo|newspaper=[[Infobae]]|first=Jose Manuel|last=Rodríguez Camarero|language=es|date=6 October 2025|access-date=4 June 2026}}</ref> and was called by [[Luis de la Fuente (footballer, born 1961)|Luis de la Fuente]] for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup|2026 World Cup]] finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/crlpp3dw14lo|title=Lamine Yamal in Spain squad but no Real players|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Elizabeth|last=Hudson|date=25 May 2026|access-date=4 June 2026}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Iglesias was nicknamed ''Panda'', after the [[Panda (Desiigner song)|song of the same name]] by rapper [[Desiigner]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lacontradeportiva.com/la-historia-de-borja-iglesias-un-panda-que-ilusiona-a-los-pericos/|title=La historia de Borja Iglesias: un 'panda' que ilusiona a los pericos|trans-title=The story of Borja Iglesias: a 'panda' that gets parakeets dreaming|publisher=La Contra Deportiva|first=Brian|last=Calvo|language=es|date=10 July 2019|access-date=15 August 2019}}</ref> He received attention for painting his fingernails black in support of [[Black Lives Matter]] in 2020; his gesture was also a statement against [[homophobia]], for which he was praised by the actor [[Brays Efe]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/futbol/brays-efe-borja-iglesias-imagina-importante-que-fue-para-7998499|title=Brays Efe: "Borja Iglesias no se imagina lo importante que fue para mí"|trans-title=Brays Efe: "Borja Iglesias could not imagine how important it was for me"|newspaper=Sport|language=es|first=Dídac|last=Peyret|date=14 June 2020|access-date=21 September 2022}}</ref>

In January 2026, after a match against Sevilla, Iglesias was subjected to homophobic slurs and hateful chanting in a car park while giving his shirt to a fan. In response, Celta launched a campaign titled "Against Hate, Together." During the subsequent home match against [[Rayo Vallecano]], over 5,000 supporters, the club's coaching staff and president [[Marián Mouriño]] all painted their nails in solidarity with the player, who clarified that he is heterosexual, stating his goal is to help "create a safe space" in men's football.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/mar/09/real-betis-borja-iglesias-interview-manchester-united-europa-league|title=Real Betis’s Borja Iglesias: ‘I first painted my nails when the Black Lives Matter protests began’|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|first=Sid|last=Lowe|date=9 March 2023|access-date=8 February 2026}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/7021257/2026/02/08/borja-iglesias-celta-vigo-nail-painting/|title=Borja Iglesias suffered homophobic abuse for painting his nails. The reaction was overwhelming|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first=Colin|last=Millar|date=8 February 2026|access-date=8 February 2026}}</ref>

When asked about his political opinions, Iglesias said "Footballers tend to lean a little bit to [[Right-wing politics|the right]] because sometimes we value that economic policy. For me, for example, that's not the only thing worth anything. What I'm trying to say is, I prefer to pay more to live in a country where I like what they do with that money".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sevilla.abc.es/alfinaldelapalmera/noticias-betis/sevi-compromiso-social-borja-iglesias-202106071428_noticia.html|title=Borja Iglesias y la ideología de los futbolistas|trans-title=Borja Iglesias and the ideology of the footballers|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=es|date=7 June 2021|access-date=21 September 2022}}</ref> In September 2025, he denounced [[Gaza genocide]]. He expressed surprise that "more importance is accorded to the cancellation of a sporting event than to a genocide," specifically addressing complaints regarding pro-Palestine protests that had impacted stages of the [[Vuelta a España]] cycling race; he defended his stance by stating that "sometimes, it is necessary to stop and claim what is mandatory, namely [[human rights]] and respect, which are often lacking," and emphasized the need to "take conscience of the injustices that exist in the world.".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/Borja-iglesias-se-dit-surpris-qu-on-accorde-plus-d-importance-a-l-annulation-d-un-evenement-sportif-qu-a-un-genocide/1592444|title=Borja Iglesias se dit "surpris qu'on accorde plus d'importance à l'annulation d'un événement sportif qu'à un génocide"|trans-title=Borja Iglesias expresses "surprise that we give more importance to cancelling a sporting event than to a genocide"|newspaper=[[L'Équipe]]|language=fr|date=11 September 2025|access-date=8 February 2026}}</ref>

